rComments: Geeta is nice and she seems like she cares about her students but, she's extremely strict and will take off marks for the smallest things. Your grammar better be perfect if you are taking this class otherwise, don't even bother trying.

She is an ok prof and she basically teaches well and explains well. But the test she made was really heavy, it was difficult and she was a tough grader. When it came to vocab test, she would stick to only one correct answer.

She tells you what content will be on the test so that's really helpful. Only problem is the course is very grammar heavy and 2 hours straight of just French grammar is super boring. Bring an ice cold bottle of water, and rest well before lecture.
teacherRatingTags: ['Clear grading criteria', 'Test heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: The course was more grammar focused than other French classes I've taken in the past. She is very detailed when it comes to letting you know what will be on the tests, there are never any surprises, so if you study what she tells you to study you should be able to get a good grade. Overall, I would say she's a pretty good french professor.

This course focuses heavily on vocabulary, and you must be very specific in the tests otherwise you won't get the marks. There are lots of tests, and a majority are memorization based. She is a good professor, but her lectures were 3 hours long, causing it to get boring. She explains everything in english if you don't understand.
if you've always been an A+ student, and hate unfairness; Don't take this class :)

Great prof. She really tried to get to know her students, and she was pretty laid back and easy going. Assigns weekly homework but it doesn't count for marks. Fair grader. She gives a lot of points for following the assignment format, so follow it closely. Also, participation counts in overall assessment grade; put up your hand, attend class, etc.

I don't understand how she expects us to memorize 26 chapters of vocabulary and 8 chapters of grammar for each test (5). If you're good at memorizing, then you'll excel in this course. First few lectures she went off-topic but she explains the meanings of words well. Take FSL362 or 364 for program requirements. Stay away from this class.

She's the sweetest lady you'll meet. Sure, her tangents are a little lengthy, but you'll learn to love them because that's how she teaches. Excellent at clarifying literally anything FrenchFrancophone related; I've never appreciated her notes so much. Mme. Paray really earned my respect.

Overall, she's really engaging and enthusiastic. Knows her stuff and explains it fairly well. She spends a bit too much time doing uselessly time-consuming things though, like reading the attendance list every single class and going on and on about how Blackboard works. We didn't have enough time to cover all the material.
Warning, XBC199 marks are highly dependent on class participation. Passion is required.

Her course is challenging, but she is EXTREMELY supportive. I'm not an Arts student, but this course was one of the most enriching of my undergrad. She replies to all emails and answers questions patiently. You can learn a lot from her - she truly is an expert and professional. She makes the effort to get to know her student  - a rarity at U of T.

One of the worst French professors I've ever had. She took marks off our assignments for no reason, would yell at us for writing on question sheets without telling us beforehand that we weren't supposed to, and test questions were designed to trick us. Whenever people voiced objections she would insist it wasn't her fault, it was the Department.

Fiction of Women of Colour was an amazing class and unique too.  With only 24 of us, it was easy to get into some really great discussions about the books we read and the Professor was knowledgeable about the works and open to all opinions besides her own.  Delightfully eccentric, she was also accommodating, helpful and understanding.
Quite helpful I found and tries to be engaging as much as you can while working within the curriculum.  Hard marker though.

An ok teacher. Teaches the material but makes no attempt to engage the class. Although attendance is mandatory, you don't learn anything in class that you couldn't learn from just reading the textbook. Turned me off from learning French.

This woman is the antithesis of a good teacher. If you want boredom, anxiety, and a classroom environment that privileges those who she deems worthy of her favours, take this woman/elf's class. She is boring, pretentious, and soporific. As she reads directly from the text, her jiggling jowels send you right to dreamland.

Made for a really boring class. She's an okay teacher, but fails to bring everyone into the class or present the material clearly and in an organized setting. If you put effort into the class, though, you'll do fine.
LOVE HER! so funny and very helpful/easygoing. makes french enjoyable and easy to learn. work load is very reasonable.
She did not like me and throughout the course I kept getting the same low mark from her.  Don't like her as a teacher.
